Don't you talk
to the general like that.

15:37.170 --> 15:39.206
You about to get
some dental work, bitch.

15:39.306 --> 15:42.175
Herschel, put those away
and wait outside.

15:42.275 --> 15:44.444
Okay, Walter.

15:44.544 --> 15:48.248
I still don't know who
some of these people are,
Mr. Blunt,

15:48.348 --> 15:52.319
but Mr. Birmingham,
I'm afraid, does make
a very strong argument.

15:52.419 --> 15:55.155
That's right, Walter!
You can't beat me.

15:55.255 --> 15:56.623
But--

15:59.259 --> 16:02.329
but I am sorry
that I hurt your feelings.

16:04.231 --> 16:06.599
Let's go, Rosalie.
Yes, Walter.

16:08.535 --> 16:09.636
Uh...

16:12.472 --> 16:14.374
Wow.

16:14.474 --> 16:15.942
Jim?

16:16.043 --> 16:19.679
Do you realize it
takes thousands of years
to create an aquifer

16:19.779 --> 16:22.882
and that more than half
of the world's aquifers
are in danger?

16:23.083 --> 16:24.384
No, I didn't.
Yeah.

16:24.484 --> 16:27.387
But what's on your head?
Is that for hearing loss?

16:27.487 --> 16:30.157
No, my hearing's fine.
It's a dog cowl.

16:30.257 --> 16:33.526
I'm wearing it
to help me focus
and not obsess about you.

16:33.626 --> 16:36.596
Oh, good,
because during
this break--

16:36.696 --> 16:38.398
Oh, okay.

16:38.498 --> 16:41.768
Jim, this is hard
for me, too...

16:41.868 --> 16:44.371
but it's important
that we start acting
more professionally.

16:44.471 --> 16:46.139
Fuck,
they're all meeting!

16:46.239 --> 16:47.240
Huh?

16:47.340 --> 16:48.641
Oh, shit.

16:48.741 --> 16:49.909
...Kazakhstan.

16:50.077 --> 16:53.113
And this is a dried-up
riverbed in, um--

16:53.213 --> 16:54.681
uh, s-somewhere.

16:54.781 --> 16:57.317
Excellent, Shelly.
Let's use that tonight.

16:57.417 --> 16:59.086
A drought primer
for our audience.

16:59.152 --> 17:01.554
Sorry we're late, Walter,
but nobody came to get us.

17:01.654 --> 17:03.123
Oh, that's fine, Celia.

17:03.223 --> 17:05.092
And, Walter,
I know you don't want
to talk about it,

17:05.158 --> 17:07.960
but I just want to say
I'm sorry about Harry
and Blunt Cock.

17:08.095 --> 17:12.632
Thank you, Martin.
Jim, what the hell
are you wearing?

17:12.732 --> 17:16.936
It's a-- a dog cowl,
Walter, to help me focus.

17:17.104 --> 17:20.673
And you're right.
Water is the biggest
story of the century.

17:20.773 --> 17:23.310
We're remaking the planet
in our own image

17:23.410 --> 17:25.178
like a--
a demented god.

17:25.278 --> 17:27.614
Demented god,
I like that.

17:27.714 --> 17:29.516
Let's get it
into the broadcast.

17:29.616 --> 17:31.984
Yes, but, Celia,
what about Rudolph?

17:32.119 --> 17:34.154
Well, you're right, Walter,
he's very elusive.

17:34.254 --> 17:36.656
Hasn't granted
an interview since 1983.

17:36.756 --> 17:38.458
I did speak
to the lawyer
and he said

17:38.558 --> 17:40.627
there is no way Rudolph
would come on Blunt Talk.

17:40.727 --> 17:44.664
Damn! I would like
to question that man.
Get him in front of me.

17:44.764 --> 17:47.434
Well, maybe you
could get to him through
his sister Margaret.

17:47.534 --> 17:50.270
She's not part
of the family business,
but she's a very public person.

17:50.370 --> 17:52.305
What do you have
in mind, Celia?

17:52.405 --> 17:54.274
The old reach-around?

17:54.374 --> 17:56.209
Yes, she's hosting
a fundraiser tonight

17:56.309 --> 17:59.979
for the Democratic
councilman, whose big issue,
interestingly enough,

18:00.147 --> 18:02.415
is for LA to have
a desalinization plant.

18:02.515 --> 18:06.253
Ooh, I like
the sound of this.

18:06.353 --> 18:08.621
Maybe I could go undercover

18:08.721 --> 18:11.258
as Walter Blunt, civilian.

18:11.358 --> 18:13.326
Can I be
your wingman, Walter?

18:13.426 --> 18:14.761
I'm very engaged
by this story

18:14.861 --> 18:18.498
and it-- it'll help me
forget my troubles.

18:18.598 --> 18:21.401
Will you take off
your cowl, Jim?

18:22.635 --> 18:23.570
Sure.

18:23.670 --> 18:25.205
Then you can come.

18:25.305 --> 18:27.174
We'll go right after
the broadcast.

18:29.342 --> 18:30.810
He shoots, he scores!

18:32.679 --> 18:35.682
Underground aquifers
supply 35%

18:35.782 --> 18:37.484
of the water used
around the globe.

18:37.584 --> 18:41.288
These reserves take thousands
of years to accumulate.

18:41.388 --> 18:43.590
The county jail
has cleared up the lice.

18:43.690 --> 18:45.758
We can interview
Adler tomorrow.

18:45.858 --> 18:48.628
I want you two
to stay late and prep.

18:48.728 --> 18:52.332
Great.
Uh, it will be
Martinelli time, right?

18:52.432 --> 18:54.867
So, like a demented god,

18:54.967 --> 18:57.670
we have altered
the planet's thermostat

18:57.770 --> 19:00.039
and are refashioning
the world in our own

19:00.207 --> 19:03.310
confused
and self-destructive image.

19:04.844 --> 19:06.779
Bah.
Sorry.

19:06.879 --> 19:09.516
Are you excited
for the fundraiser?

19:09.616 --> 19:11.918
I'm going for work,
Herschel, not pleasure.

19:13.720 --> 19:15.255
Look, if you can't
get it this time,

19:15.355 --> 19:16.623
I'll do it myself.

19:16.723 --> 19:18.358
It's not a problem.

19:18.458 --> 19:19.859
I want to do a good job.

19:19.959 --> 19:21.894
I know I have
big shoes to fill.

19:25.965 --> 19:28.301
Herschel.
Hmm?

19:28.401 --> 19:30.570
What is that
I'm feeling?

19:32.439 --> 19:34.574
My brass knuckle.

19:36.243 --> 19:38.578
I'll tie my own tie.

19:39.479 --> 19:41.248
All right.

19:48.921 --> 19:51.358
...93...

19:51.458 --> 19:53.626
94...

19:53.726 --> 19:55.495
95...

19:55.595 --> 19:57.430
Harry, where are ya?

19:57.530 --> 19:58.965
Stanley and I need
more tequila.

19:59.065 --> 20:01.234
Or bourbon
or rubbing alcohol.

20:01.234 --> 20:01.268
Or bourbon
or rubbing alcohol.
Something right away.

20:01.268 --> 20:02.702
Something right away.

20:02.802 --> 20:04.571
Shit, he's going
to slow us down.

20:04.671 --> 20:07.039
My family hates it
when I'm late.

20:07.240 --> 20:09.008
One moment, Ronnie.

20:09.208 --> 20:12.379
96, 97, 98, 99, 100.

20:12.479 --> 20:14.080
There, all done, Major.

20:14.281 --> 20:16.148
Harry!
What?

20:16.249 --> 20:18.150
You called me Major again.

20:18.251 --> 20:20.320
Oh, God,
I'm so sorry.

20:20.420 --> 20:22.622
You're longing for him.

20:22.722 --> 20:26.493
Red, I need tequila
and baby oil and the remote.

20:26.593 --> 20:28.328
I'm coming, Ronnie.

20:30.497 --> 20:31.898
I'm sorry.

20:40.239 --> 20:41.674
Ah, thank you.

20:41.774 --> 20:43.710
Hey, Jim, slow down.

20:43.810 --> 20:45.745
That's your fifth
rum and Coke.

20:45.845 --> 20:48.681
Is that a lot?
I don't get out much.

20:49.816 --> 20:51.618
Good evening, everyone.

20:55.988 --> 20:59.426
Welcome to a night
of bidding, dancing,

20:59.526 --> 21:02.161
drinking,
and bidding some more.

21:02.329 --> 21:04.331
I'm Margaret Rudolph,
your host

21:04.364 --> 21:07.800
and also your auctioneer.
Hey, there she is.

21:09.336 --> 21:11.771
Now, unfortunately,
Councilman Sandler

21:11.871 --> 21:15.174
can't make it tonight.
He has shingles.

21:15.375 --> 21:17.410
Again.

21:17.510 --> 21:21.414
But he appreciates
your support very, very much.

21:21.514 --> 21:24.451
Are-- are we applauding
shingles?

21:24.551 --> 21:26.953
Shh. That's a very
painful condition.

21:27.053 --> 21:29.956
Now, our first
bid item tonight

21:30.056 --> 21:33.793
is a very interesting piece
from a local artist,

21:33.893 --> 21:37.530
Cindy Lockwood, who cites
among her influences

21:37.630 --> 21:39.031
the great Allan Jones.

21:39.131 --> 21:43.202
It's called
Have a Seat, Please.

21:43.370 --> 21:46.706
And we'll start
the bidding at $5,000.

21:46.806 --> 21:49.008
All right, who's gonna
kick us off?

21:49.108 --> 21:52.512
Kick things off, Walter.
That'll win her trust.

21:52.612 --> 21:54.881
Anyone?
Yes, great thinking.

21:54.981 --> 21:57.917
Yeah.
Oh, there we go.
There we go.

21:58.017 --> 21:59.452
We have our first bidder.

21:59.552 --> 22:01.554
All right,
do I hear 5,500?

22:01.654 --> 22:04.524
5,500?

22:06.058 --> 22:08.495
Well, then 5,000
going once,

22:08.595 --> 22:11.564
going twice,
sold to the gentleman
in the front,

22:11.664 --> 22:14.901
who I believe
is Mr. Walter Blunt,

22:15.001 --> 22:17.570
my favorite newscaster.

22:24.911 --> 22:26.979
Hey, hey.
Check this out.

22:27.079 --> 22:29.416
Oh, Walter's going
to love this.

22:29.516 --> 22:32.318
Duncan Adler has been writing
letters to the LA Times

22:32.419 --> 22:34.854
for years about
Rudolph Global's
almond farms

22:34.954 --> 22:37.023
sucking all the water
up out-- what?

22:38.825 --> 22:40.927
What were you doing?
Were you sniffing my hair?

22:41.027 --> 22:44.664
Yes, I was.
I'm sorry. Jeez.

22:44.764 --> 22:46.933
Okay, why were you
smelling my hair?

22:47.033 --> 22:50.102
Does my scalp
smell yeasty like
old popcorn?

22:50.202 --> 22:53.540
No. No, it's because--

22:53.640 --> 22:54.941
Martin?

22:55.041 --> 22:57.644
Uh, because I have
a crush on you, Shelly.

22:57.744 --> 22:58.978
Please don't hate me.

22:59.078 --> 23:00.913
Oh, God.

23:01.013 --> 23:03.783
I mean, I knew
something was going on.

23:03.883 --> 23:05.452
When did this start?

23:05.552 --> 23:09.288
Um, when I touched
your breasts during
your cancer scare.

23:09.489 --> 23:11.023
Oh, yeah?
Yeah.

23:11.123 --> 23:12.992
'Cause it felt good?
It was, like, right away.

23:13.092 --> 23:15.094
I was like, pfft!
Yeah, 'cause it's nice and--

23:15.194 --> 23:17.864
Supple.
Got a lot of texture.
Well, drop it!

23:17.964 --> 23:21.100
We're all going nuts here.
Jim loves Celia.

23:21.200 --> 23:23.570
I love Celia.
Celia loves Walter.

23:23.670 --> 23:25.337
Walter loves Harry.
Rosalie loves you.

23:25.472 --> 23:27.039
Wait, what?
What-- what do you mean?

23:27.139 --> 23:28.941
Oh, you know she still
pines for you,

23:29.041 --> 23:31.077
but she's--
she's tough.

23:31.177 --> 23:34.046
Anyway, drop it.
You have a girlfriend.

23:34.146 --> 23:36.148
I know.
Ugh, I'm-- ugh.

23:36.248 --> 23:41.020
I won't fantasize
about you sexually
ever again, I promise.

23:41.320 --> 23:44.524
Well, let's not make
promises we can't keep.

23:44.624 --> 23:47.794
I mean, I'm okay with
being naked in your mind.

23:47.894 --> 23:50.096
I am meant
to be worshipped.

23:51.631 --> 23:53.800
Get back to work.
Right.

23:58.738 --> 24:01.741
Do you see
Ms. Rudolph anywhere?

24:03.109 --> 24:04.611
No.

24:06.178 --> 24:08.515
Excuse me, young man.
Hmm?

24:08.581 --> 24:09.782
Would you like to dance?

24:09.882 --> 24:12.719
Um, sure.

24:12.819 --> 24:14.521
Uh, I'd-- I'd love to.

24:28.768 --> 24:30.603
Excuse me.

24:30.703 --> 24:32.639
Ms. Rudolph,
I-I was wondering

24:32.739 --> 24:35.875
if my new chair
came with a dance?

24:35.975 --> 24:38.978
Yes, and an apology.

24:39.078 --> 24:41.648
I'm so sorry
you ended up
with that thing.

24:41.748 --> 24:43.616
Oh, please.

24:48.555 --> 24:50.757
You're light
on your feet, handsome.

24:50.857 --> 24:52.592
Thanks.

24:52.692 --> 24:54.060
Are you a prostitute?

24:54.160 --> 24:56.195
What?
N-no.

24:56.295 --> 24:59.131
S-sorry.
I was just asking.

24:59.231 --> 25:02.068
The young men
at these things
are usually working boys.

25:02.168 --> 25:04.270
Oh, well,
not-- not me.

25:05.905 --> 25:07.674
I don't know
what's happening.

25:07.774 --> 25:10.476
Everyone at work is kind
of losing their minds
and breaking up.

25:10.577 --> 25:13.079
Jim and Celia,
Harry and Walter.

25:13.179 --> 25:16.115
When we hate ourselves,
it's hard to love others.

25:16.215 --> 25:18.284
Oh, God,
is there any hope?

25:18.384 --> 25:21.854
Yes, we have to face
our nightmares.

25:21.954 --> 25:26.793
So I was thinking
that if you want to go
down on me, you can.

25:28.628 --> 25:30.429
Really? Now?
Yes.

25:30.597 --> 25:32.264
You won't be in
your oral stage forever.

25:39.105 --> 25:41.207
Ready?
Ready.

25:48.748 --> 25:50.717
Oh, Martin.

25:50.817 --> 25:53.686
Oh, Martin!

25:57.156 --> 25:59.125
You know,
I am really interested

25:59.225 --> 26:01.794
in your candidate's
position

26:01.894 --> 26:03.830
on desalinization.

26:05.732 --> 26:08.635
Can we just dance
for a little while,
Mr. Blunt,

26:08.668 --> 26:10.870
and forget
the world's troubles?

26:10.970 --> 26:13.072
Yes, of course.

26:13.172 --> 26:16.743
And by the way,
you can call me Walter.

26:16.843 --> 26:19.078
All right, Walter.

26:19.178 --> 26:21.480
But I would like
to get together sometime

26:21.648 --> 26:24.951
and we can talk drought
all you want.

26:25.051 --> 26:28.554
Or we could raid
your wine cellar

26:28.655 --> 26:31.190
and actually have
a good time.

26:31.290 --> 26:34.126
That sounds very nice.
Mmm.

26:38.164 --> 26:41.133
Harry, Sylvia,
what are you doing here?

26:41.233 --> 26:43.002
Oh, hi, Walter.

26:43.102 --> 26:45.237
Councilman Sandler's
my second cousin.

26:45.337 --> 26:49.108
And Ronnie--
well, Ronnie gave me
the night off, sir,

26:49.208 --> 26:53.012
so Sylvia and I
could go dancing.

26:53.112 --> 26:54.947
Very nice, Harry.

26:58.217 --> 27:00.252
Did you know
he was going to be here?

27:01.688 --> 27:04.891
No, your family
invited us.

27:04.991 --> 27:07.059
Who was that?

27:07.159 --> 27:09.295
Oh, he's...

27:09.395 --> 27:12.198
a-- a dear, dear friend.

27:14.433 --> 27:17.569
They say that
two stars on opposite
ends of the universe

27:17.704 --> 27:20.106
can still be drawn
to each other.

27:20.206 --> 27:22.341
Maybe that's like
me and the major.

27:22.441 --> 27:25.912
Oh, you mean
quantum entanglement.

27:45.064 --> 27:46.733
Celia?

27:48.334 --> 27:51.237
Oh, Evelyn.
I didn't want
to wake you, tiger.

27:51.337 --> 27:53.572
Are you--
are you leaving?
Yeah, I got to go.

27:53.740 --> 27:57.309
I left you
a gift on the desk.
Knock yourself out.

27:57.409 --> 28:00.079
I t-- I told you, Evelyn,
I'm not a prostitute.

28:00.179 --> 28:02.849
You are now.

28:04.216 --> 28:07.119
No, I'm not.
